<div class="fluid-row" id="header">



<h1 class="title toc-ignore">How to use Python and R in the same RMarkdown document with <i>feather</i></h1>
</div>

Note: this script is available in full on github: <a href="https://github.com/nickmalleson/surf/blob/master/projects/extras/R_Python.Rmd">github.com/nickmalleson/surf/blob/master/projects/extras/R_Python.Rmd</a><br/><br/>

<p>This is a small example of how to use R and Python together in the same R Markdown document</p>
<p>This uses the <a href="https://blog.rstudio.com/2016/03/29/feather/">feather</a> library that allows R and python to share data by writing binary files.</p>
<div id="initialise" class="section level2">
<h2>Initialise</h2>
<pre class="r"><code>library(feather) # To allow python and R to share data</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="create-some-data-with-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Create some data with R</h2>
<p>For this example weâ€™ll just create a list of random numbers to be manipulated in R and Python (code frome <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19352267/r-create-a-data-frame-with-random-numbers-in-each-column">here</a>).</p>
<p>Make a data frame with two columns and 1000 rows.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>data &lt;- data.frame(replicate(2,sample(0:10,1000,rep=TRUE)))

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
hist(data$X1)
hist(data$X2)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="write-the-data-using-feather" class="section level2">
<h2>Write the data using feather</h2>
<p>Write out the <code>data</code> dataframe using Feather so that it can be read in and manipulated by Python.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>write_feather(data, path=&quot;./data.feather&quot;)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="read-and-process-the-data-in-python" class="section level2">
<h2>Read and process the data in python</h2>
<p>Now the neat bit - use python to read the data from R, do something with it (weâ€™ll just make a new column) and then write it back out.</p>
<p>Note that in the R Markdown document, you can specify a particular python engine to use. E.g. the following would use an anaconda environment called â€˜py35â€™:</p>
<pre><code>{python engine.path=&quot;/Users/nick/anaconda2/envs/py35/bin/python&quot;}</code></pre>
<p>Youâ€™ll have to change that to match your own setup if you want to run this script.</p>
<p>Which ever python environment you use, you have to have the <code>feather</code> library installed. You can install it as normal, with something like:</p>
<p><code>pip install feather-format</code></p>
<pre class="python"><code>
import feather

# Read in the data frame
data = feather.read_dataframe(&quot;./data.feather&quot;)

# Create a new column by multiplying the first two columns:
data.loc[:,'X3'] = data.loc[:,'X1'] * data.loc[:,'X2']

# Write out the data using feather
feather.write_dataframe(data, &quot;./data.feather&quot;)
</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="re-read-the-data-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Re-read the data in R</h2>
<p>Now that weâ€™ve processed it in python, re-read it using R.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>new.data &lt;- read_feather(&quot;./data.feather&quot;)

hist(new.data$X3)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Thatâ€™s it!</p>
<p>OK thatâ€™s a very simple example, but the ability to use either language in the same R Markdown document, and to share data, is extremely powerful.</p>
</div>
